</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Myocardial fat is often seen at cardiac computed tomography (CT) and magnetic resonance (MR) imaging of healthy adults and patients with myocardial diseases. Physiologic myocardial fat develops with aging and is commonly seen at CT in the anterolateral right ventricular (RV) free wall and RV outflow tract with normal or thickened RV myocardium and a normal-sized RV in elderly patients. Pathologic conditions with myocardial fat include healed myocardial infarction (MI); arrhythmogenic RV cardiomyopathy or dysplasia (ARVC); and others, such as cardiac lipoma, lipomatous hypertrophy of the interatrial septum, tuberous sclerosis complex, dilated cardiomyopathy, and cardiomyopathy with muscular dystrophy. In patients with healed MI, CT and MR imaging show fat in left ventricular myocardium that is of normal thickness or thin and follows the distribution of the coronary artery; CT often depicts fat in mostly subendocardial regions. In patients with ARVC, characteristic CT and MR imaging findings include a thin RV outflow tract and free wall caused by subepicardial fatty infiltration; fat in the RV moderator band, trabeculae, and ventricular septum; and RV enlargement and wall motion abnormality. Recognition of patient age, characteristic locations of myocardial fat, myocardial thickness, and ventricular size helps in differentiating physiologic and pathologic myocardial fat at cardiac imaging; findings of wall motion abnormality and late gadolinium enhancement at MR imaging help narrow the diagnosis.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2010</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.306105519">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.306105519">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig01" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig01.jpeg" height="734" width="934" aria-labelledby="fig01" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Physiologic myocardial fat in a 73-year-old man who died of lung cancer. Photomicrograph (original magnification, ×40; hematoxylin-eosin stain) of an autopsy specimen shows fatty infiltration in the perivascular areas of the myocardium in the RV outflow tract (RVOT).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig01">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig02a.jpeg" height="922" width="1229" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig02a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig02b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig02b.jpeg" height="861" width="1152" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig02b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig03a.jpeg" height="1794" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig03a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig03b.jpeg" height="1737" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig03b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig03c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig03c.jpeg" height="1751" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig03c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig04a.jpeg" height="982" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig04a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig04b.jpeg" height="1122" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig04b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig04c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig04c.jpeg" height="1067" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig04c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig05a.jpeg" height="1800" width="1745" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig05a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig05b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig05b.jpeg" height="1800" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig05b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig06" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig06.jpeg" height="1602" width="1579" aria-labelledby="fig06" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6</span> Physiologic myocardial fat in an 81-year-old woman without cardiac disease who had a body mass index of 23.5 kg/m<sup>2</sup>. Axial precontrast CT image shows fat (arrow) in the LV apex.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig06">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig07a.jpeg" height="842" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig07a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig07b.jpeg" height="1280" width="609" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig07b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig07c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig07c.jpeg" height="847" width="1280" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig07c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig08" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig08.jpeg" height="1478" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig08" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8</span> Healed MI caused by total occlusion of the left anterior descending coronary artery (infarct age = 15 years) in a 73-year-old man. Short-axis contrast-enhanced CT image shows subendocardial fat (arrows) in the distribution of the left anterior descending coronary artery (anteroseptal wall).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig08">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig09" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig09.jpeg" height="1489" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig09" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9</span> Healed MI caused by total occlusion of the right coronary artery (infarct age = 20 years) in a 71-year-old man. Short-axis contrast-enhanced CT image shows fat (arrows) caused by healed MI in the subendocardial inferior wall of the RV and the RV side of the interventricular septum. In addition, there is fat in the subendocardial lateral wall of the RV (arrowheads), a finding that could also be due to the healed MI.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig09">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig10.jpeg" height="1648" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig10" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10</span> Healed MI of unknown onset caused by total occlusion of the left anterior descending coronary artery in a 61-year-old man. Short-axis contrast-enhanced CT image shows middle layer fat (arrow) in the anterior wall of the LV. A small amount of LV thrombus (*) is also demonstrated.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig10">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig11.jpeg" height="1650" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig11" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11</span> Healed MI of unknown onset in a 64-year-old man after percutaneous transluminal coronary angioplasty of the right coronary artery. Short-axis contrast-enhanced CT image shows subepicardial fat (arrow) in the inferior wall of the LV.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig11">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.306105519/asset/images/105519fig12a.jpeg" height="1766" width="1800" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> <!-- There is no content. --><div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.306105519&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><im